      "model": "gemini-2.5-flash",
      "used_fallback": false,
      "mode": "concept",
      "answer": "IV crush happens when an option's implied volatility, or IV, drops sharply after a major event like an earnings report or a drug trial announcement.\n\nBefore the event, options prices often get inflated because everyone expects a big move in the stock. After the news is out, that uncertainty disappears, and so does the extra premium built into the options.\n\nFor options buyers, IV crush can be a significant risk. Even if the stock moves in your favor, the drop in IV can sometimes offset or even outweigh your gains, making it harder to profit.",
