      "used_fallback": false,
      "mode": "simplify",
      "answer": "Okay, think of it like this: Before a big event, like an earnings report, there's a lot of guesswork and excitement about how the stock might move. This makes options more expensive because of all that uncertainty.\n\nOnce the event happens and the news is out, the mystery is gone. All that built-up excitement and expectation (which is what implied volatility represents) quickly deflates. This sudden drop in implied volatility makes options prices fall, often quite a bit, even if the stock itself didn't move as expected. That's IV crush.",
